uws.job.serializer.filter

Class JobListFilter

  • java.lang.Object
    • uws.job.serializer.filter.JobListFilter

  • public class JobListFilter
extends java.lang.Object

    Let filter a list of jobs according to the filter parameters given in an HttpServletRequest.

    Only the following HTTP-GET parameters will generate a job filter:

    • PHASE: a single legal phase is expected. Only jobs having this phase will pass through this filter.
      Note: Several PHASE parameters with different execution phases may be provided. Their effect will be joint with a logical OR (so, all jobs of one of the given phases will pass the filter).
    • AFTER: an ISO-8601 date is expected. Only jobs started (strictly) after this date will pass through the filter.
      Note: If several AFTER parameters are provided, only the one with the most recent date will be taken into account. For instance: ?AFTER=2015-01-01T12:00:00Z&AFTER=2014-01-01T12:00:00Z will be interpreted as just 1 AFTER filter with the date 2015-01-01T12:00:00Z.
    • LAST: a positive integer number is expected. Only the LAST most recently started jobs will pass through the filter. The jobs will be sorted by ascending startTime.
      Note 1: If several LAST parameters are provided, only the smallest positive (and not null) value will be taken into account.
      Note 2: Only started jobs will be returned if this filter is specified. This means that only PENDING jobs are rejected.

    IMPORTANT Note: If no PHASE filter is specified, a default one rejecting ARCHIVED filter is set by default. This is specified in UWS 1.1 standard so that being backward compatible with the version 1.0 of the standard in which no ARCHIVED phase existed.

    Since:
    4.2
    Version:
    4.2 (10/2015)
    Author:
    Grégory Mantelet (ARI)

      • sortComp

        protected java.util.Comparator<UWSJob> sortComp
        Indicate how jobs must be sorted in the jobList list. If NULL, jobs are merely added at the end of the list: no order.

      • topSize

        protected int topSize
        Indicate how many of the first jobs of the list jobList must be really retained. If negative or null, all jobs are of the filtered list are returned.

      • reverseOrder

        protected boolean reverseOrder
        Indicate if the jobs of the jobList list must be returned from the beginning to the end (false) or from the end to the beginning (true). If topSize have a positive and not null value, this attribute will then apply on the topSize first jobs: if false jobs from 0 to topSize are returned, otherwise they are returned from topSize to 0.

      • JobListFilter

        public JobListFilter(javax.servlet.http.HttpServletRequest request)

        Build a filter for a whole list of jobs. This filter will actually be composed of several Job filters, in function of the HTTP-GET parameters specified in the given HTTP request.

        Only the following HTTP-GET parameters will generate a job filter:

        • PHASE: a single legal phase is expected. Only jobs having this phase will pass through this filter.
          Note: Several PHASE parameters with different execution phases may be provided. Their effect will be joint with a logical OR (so, all jobs of one of the given phases will pass the filter).
        • AFTER: an ISO-8601 date is expected. Only jobs started (strictly) after this date will pass through the filter.
          Note: If several AFTER parameters are provided, only the one with the most recent date will be taken into account. For instance: ?AFTER=2015-01-01T12:00:00Z&AFTER=2014-01-01T12:00:00Z will be interpreted as just 1 AFTER filter with the date 2015-01-01T12:00:00Z.
        • LAST: a positive integer number is expected. Only the LAST most recently started jobs will pass through the filter. The jobs will be sorted by ascending startTime.
          Note 1: If several LAST parameters are provided, only the smallest positive (and not null) value will be taken into account.
          Note 2: Only started jobs will be returned if this filter is specified. This means that only PENDING jobs are rejected.

        IMPORTANT Note: If no PHASE filter is specified, a default one rejecting ARCHIVED filter is set by default. This is specified in UWS 1.1 standard so that being backward compatible with the version 1.0 of the standard in which no ARCHIVED phase existed.

        Parameters:
        request - An HTTP request in which HTTP-GET parameters correspond to Job filters to create.

    • Method Detail

      • addJob

        protected final void addJob(UWSJob job)

        Add the given job in the temporary internal list of filtered jobs by preserving the specified sorting.

        This function added the job at the end of the list IF no sort is required. Otherwise, a binary search is performed and the job is added at the right place in the list so that keeping the list sorted.

        Parameters:
        job - The job to keep in the displayable job list.

      • filter

        public java.util.Iterator<UWSJob> filter(java.util.Iterator<UWSJob> jobList)
        Filter (and eventually sort and/or limit in size) the given list of jobs.
        Parameters:
        jobList - Job list to filter.
        Returns:
        The filtered (and eventually sorted/limited) job list.

      • match

        protected final boolean match(UWSJob job)

        Tell whether the given job matches all the job filters. In other words, this function operates a logical AND between all listed filters.

        Note: If the given job is NULL, false will be returned. In case of error while evaluating one of the filters on the given job, false will be returned as well.

        Parameters:
        job - A job to filter.
        Returns:
        true if the job matches all the filters, false otherwise.
